data.notes: Available during accumulation phase. Upon death of owner, benefit will be equal to the contract value. There is an Extended Legacy Program, offered by issuer, for beneficiaries to continue the contract after the death of the owner. The program is not available under rollover contracts and with any other than 5-year settlement option. Upon election, beneficiary may choose to receive the death benefit under either 1) a 5-year settlement option (starting from death of owner); or 2) in the form of withdrawals for a longer period of time. Issuer will charge the beneficiary an annual base contract expense of 1.15%. This charge is deducted daily from the average daily ending net asset value allocated to the Variable Portfolios.
data.name: Contract Value death benefit
data.partialWithdrawals: Withdrawals will reduce benefit base in same proportion.
data.spousalContinuationOption: Surviving spouse may elect to continue benefit after death of owner.
data.change: Once elected may not be changed.

data.notes: Available during the accumulation phase. Upon the death of an owner (without living benefit), the benefit will be greatest of -1) contract value, 2) net purchase payments, increased by subsequent purchase payments, adjusted for withdrawals (includes advisory fees; if applicable), or 3) highest contract value on any contract anniversary prior to owner's 83rd birthday or death. Upon death of owner (with living benefit), benefit will be greatest of -1) contract value, 2) purchase payments reduced by - a) any withdrawal adjustments if living benefit is not terminated, or b) any withdrawals prior to the date living benefit is terminated, or 3) highest contract value on any contract anniversary prior to owner's 83rd birthday or death reduced by - a) any Withdrawal Adjustments since contract anniversary if living benefit is not terminated, b) any withdrawal adjustments since contract anniversary, prior to the date the Living Benefit is terminated and reduced for a withdrawals in the same proportion that the withdrawal reduced the contract value on the date of such withdrawal on or after the date the living benefit is terminated and The Maximum Anniversary Value death benefit can only be elected prior to annuitants 81st birthday.

data.availPrescribedAssetLocation: Owner must select an Asset Allocation Program.
data.availRestrictionFxdAccount: Owner must allocate a certain percentage of each purchase payment and spousal continuation contribution to Fixed Account.
data.availWhenAdded: No longer available for new purchases.
data.change: Once elected may not be changed.
data.effectChangeOwnership: Change in ownership will result in termination of rider except under certain conditions.
data.gmwbCancellation: May be cancelled on 5th anniversary or any quarterly rider anniversary thereafter.
data.gmwbTermination: Benefit will automatically terminate upon earliest of - 1) annuitization, 2) surrender, 3) death, or 4) benefit base reduces to zero.
data.spousalContinuationOption: Surviving spouse may elect to continue benefit after death of owner under joint life option.
data.subsequentPremium: Subsequent Eligible Purchase Payments increase the Benefit Base and Income Credit Base by dollar for dollar. The MAW and Protected Income Payment amounts are increased by the appropriate % multiplied by the amount of the subsequent Eligible Purchase Payment. Total Purchase Payments are limited to $1,500,000 without prior approval.
data.partialWithdrawals: When withdrawals in a rider year exceed the MAW amount, the Income Base and Income Credit Base are reduced in the same proportion that the contract value is reduced for the excess withdrawal. The MAW amount is reset to the MAW % multiplied by the new Benefit Base.
data.reqdMinDistributions: RMD withdrawals in excess of the MAW amount are not considered to be excess withdrawals.
data.benefitDescription: The rider provides a guaranteed lifetime income.
data.benefitBaseGeneral: Living Benefit lock in the greater of two values to determine the Income Base. The Income Base is the basis for the Covered Persons' guaranteed lifetime benefit which must be taken in a series of withdrawals. Income Base is initially equal to the first Eligible Purchase Payment, thereafter, automatically locked in on each Benefit Year Anniversary, to the greater of (1) the highest Anniversary Value, or (2) the current Income Base increased by any available Income Credit.
data.benefitBaseNoWithdrawal: Issuer may increase benefit base by 6%, until 12th rider anniversary, if withdrawals taken during benefit year are less than or equal to annual benefit payments. Income Credit Base will be set equal to greater of - 1) income base based on maximum anniversary value, or 2) income base plus income credit. If no withdrawal is taken, the Minimum Income Base on the 12th Benefit Year anniversary is the greater of - a) current Income Base, or if the First and Subsequent Extensions were elected, the Income Base calculated based on the maximum Anniversary Value; and b) Minimum Income Base.
data.benefitBaseEnhanceStep: On the 12th contract anniversary, the Income Base will be increased to at least 200% of the Purchase Payments made in the first contract year, provided no withdrawals are taken prior to that anniversary.
data.notes: 100% of purchase payments made during first contract year are taken into consideration in determining the Eligible Purchase Payments. If contract value has been reduced to zero or the Latest Annuity Date is reached, the Protected Income Payment Percentage represents the percentage of Income Base used to calculate the Protected Income Payment that will be receive each year over the remaining lifetime of the Covered Person(s). The Protected Income Payment Percentage differs depending on whether there are one or two Covered Person(s), the age of the Covered Person(s) at the time of first withdrawal and, for those taking withdrawals before age 65, whether a highest Anniversary Value is attained after the Covered Person(s)' 65th birthday and the income option elected. Effective January 15, 2016, if owner elect this rider, and contract issue date is on January 23, 2012 or later, Issuer will not accept subsequent purchase payments after 12 months (60 months if contract issued date January 23, 2012) from contract issue date.
data.chargeNotes: Rider fees is calculated as a percentage of the Income Base and is deducted on quarterly anniversaries of the rider effective date and begin on the date the rider takes effect. The quarterly fee rate will not decrease or increase by more than 0.0625% each quarter.
data.stateNotes: May not be available in all states.

data.withdrawalNotes: Income percentages displayed above for Income Options 1&2 are available while the account value is greater than $0. If the 1st withdrawal was taken prior to age 65, Protected Income Payments for both Income Options 1 & 2 will be 3%. data.restrictionOnSubAcctNotes: Owner must allocate contribution of 10% to the secure value account and up to 90% in the sub-accounts under Group A and B above. Of these 90% owner may invest max 50% in the sub-accounts under Group B.

Living benefit depends on the income option elected, whether 1) single or joint, 2) age of the covered person(s) at the time of first withdrawal, and 3) contract value.
data.benefitBaseNoWithdrawal: If no withdrawals have been taken, the Income Base is increased to the Step-up Value immediately, on daily basis.
data.benefitBaseWithdrawal: After the first withdrawal, while both the Income Base and the contract values are greater than zero, the Income Base may only be increased on the Benefit Year Anniversary dates, looking back at the prior Benefit Years Step-up Values, or, if one or more Excess Withdrawals have been taken in that Benefit Year, to the highest Step-up Value since the last Excess Withdrawal.

If the 1st withdrawal was taken prior to age 65, Protected Income Payments for both Income Options 1 & 2 will be 2.75%. This rate will increase to 4% if the income base is increased due to an account value step-up at age 65 or later while there is account value in the contract.

data.subsequentPremium: Subsequent Eligible Purchase Payments increase the benefit base dollar for dollar and the MAW amount by the MAW % multiplied by the amount of the subsequent purchase payment.

data.benefitDescription: The rider provides a guaranteed lifetime income plus the opportunity to increase income by locking in the greater of either the contract's highest anniversary value, or an annual Income Credit.
data.benefitBaseGeneral: Living Benefit locks in the greater of two values to determine the Income Base. The Income Base is the basis for the Covered Persons' guaranteed lifetime benefit which must be taken in a series of withdrawals. Income Base is initially equal to the first Eligible Purchase Payment, thereafter, automatically locked in on each Benefit Year Anniversary, to the greater of - 1) highest Anniversary Value, or 2) current Income Base increased by any available Income Credit.
data.benefitBaseNoWithdrawal: Prior to the Activation Date, if no withdrawals are taken during the Benefit Year, the Income Credit applied to the Income Base is not reduced. If the Activation Date is after the 12th contract anniversary, and owner do not take any withdrawals during the first 12 years, owner will be eligible for the Minimum Income Base on the 12th Benefit Year Anniversary. Issuer may increase benefit base by 5.25%, on each rider anniversary. Initially the Income Credit Base is equal to the first Purchase Payment, thereafter increases by the subsequent purchase payment received and is reduced proportionately for any withdrawals taken prior to the Activation Date and Excess Withdrawals taken on or after the Activation Date.
data.benefitBaseWithdrawal: On or after the Activation Date, the Income Credit is reduced but not eliminated in any Benefit Year in which cumulative withdrawals are less than 5.25% of the Income Base and not greater than the Maximum Annual Withdrawal Amount applicable to the income option elected under the rider, thereby providing a guarantee that income can continue to increase during the first 12 years even after starting withdrawals. After the first 12 years, the Income Base may only increase to the Higher Anniversary Value.
data.benefitBaseEnhanceStep: On the 12th contract anniversary, the Income Base will be increased to at least 200% of the Purchase Payments in the first contract year, provided no withdrawals are taken prior to that anniversary.
data.benefitBaseOther: If you elect Polaris Income Plus Flex and you change your Income Option on the Activation Date, One-time opportunity to change the Income Option for an additional annual fee of 0.25%.
data.notes: Maximum Annual Withdrawal Percentage represents the maximum percentage of the income base that can be withdrawn each benefit year on or after the Activation Date and while the contract value is greater than zero,without reducing the Income Base and the Income Credit Base. If contract value is reduced to zero, after the Activation Date but Income Base is greater than zero, the Protected Income Payment Percentage represents the percentage of the Income Base received each rider year, until the death of the covered person. The MAWA and PIP are determined by three factors - 1) Single or Joint Life, 2) Age of the covered person at the time of first withdrawal, or 3) the Income option elected.
data.withdrawalNotes: For the PIP Income Options 1 & 2, Protected Income Payment Percentage will be 4.0% if the Income Base is increased to a new Highest Anniversary Value on or after the covered person's (65th birthday).
data.chargeNotes: Rider fees are deducted on quarterly anniversaries of the rider effective date and begin on the date the rider takes effect.
data.feeOption: The fee rate can increase or decrease no more than 0.10% each quarter (0.40%/4).
data.restrictionOnSubAcctNotes: Owner must allocate 10% in Secure Value Account and remaining 90% must be in the specified sub-accounts and DCA fixed account under group A & B, where 50% of this 90% allocation must be made under the Var Invt options specified under group B.

data.reqdMinDistributions: RMD withdrawals in excess of the MAW amount are not considered to be excess withdrawals.
data.benefitDescription: Rider provides lifetime guaranteed income stream plus the opportunity to increase income by locking in step-up values. Owner have 3 different Income Options to choose from and rider offers flexibility to make one-time change to owner's initial elections of 1) covered person and 2) income option on the Activation Date.
data.benefitBaseGeneral: Income Base is determined by the Step-up Values on daily basis. Initially the Income Base is equal to the initial purchase payment, thereafter is increased by each subsequent Purchase Payment received, and is reduced proportionally by any withdrawals taken prior to the Activation Date and Excess Withdrawals taken on or after the Activation Date. Additionally, issuer provides Minimum Income Base on every benefit year anniversary and Daily Step-up Values, prior to the activation date. Income Base is used to determine the Maximum Withdrawal Amount that can be withdrawn under the rider. Maximum amount withdrawn on or after the activation date, while contract value is greater than zero, is equal to the Maximum Annual Withdrawal Percentage multiplied by the Income Base. Maximum amount withdrawn if contract value reduces to zero, but Income Base is greater than zero after the Activation Date, is equal to the Protected Income Payment Percentage multiplied by the Income Base.
data.benefitBaseNoWithdrawal: Prior to the Activation Date, the Income Base is increased daily to the Step-up values and by subsequent purchase payments, if any. Additionally, Income Base is increased to at least the Minimum Income Base on the Benefit Year Anniversary compounding at 6% annually.
data.benefitBaseWithdrawal: On or after the Activation Date, Income Base is increased only on the Benefit Year Anniversary by looking back to the Higher Step-up Value since the Activation Date.
data.benefitBaseEnhanceStep: The Step-up value is used to determine the Income Base and is initially equals to the contract value. Then on any day, prior to the activation date, if Contract Value is greater than the Income Base, the Income Base is stepped up to that Contract Value.
data.notes: Owner can change the Income Option on the Activation Date (quarterly fee rate can increase no more than 0.1625%) the Lifetime Income Option Change Fee will be assessed and deducted from your contract value starting on the first Benefit Quarter Anniversary following the Activation Date and quarterly thereafter.
data.withdrawalNotes: Protected Income Payment Percentage will be 4.50% for single life & 4.25% for joint life for option I, if the Income Base is increased to a new Highest Anniversary Value on or after the covered person's (65th birthday).
data.chargeNotes: Rider fee is calculated as a percentage of the Income Base and is deducted on quarterly anniversaries of the rider effective date and begin on the date the rider takes effect.
data.initialResetText: If one or more Excess Withdrawals have been taken in that Benefit Year, the Income Base is increased on the Benefit Year Anniversary by looking back to the highest Step-up Value since the last Excess Withdrawal.
data.feeOption: The fee rate can increase or decrease no more than 0.10% each quarter (0.40%/4) and The change in fee percentage is determined by the change in Volatility Index (VIX) decreases or increases, the fee rate will decrease or increase accordingly.
data.restrictionOnSubAcctNotes: Owner must allocate 10% in Secure Value Account and the remaining 90% must be distributed as following Variable Portfolios in 1)Asset Allocation Portfolios or else by choosing 2) Build your own allocation, investment here must be as either 18% to 90% to the options available under Group A, maximum up to 72% to the options available under Group B or maximum up to 27% to the options available under Group C.

data.name: Polaris Income Max
data.availPrescribedAssetLocation: Owner must select an Asset Allocation Program.
data.availRestrictionFxdAccount: 20% of the total contribution made into the contract must be allocated to the Secure Value Account, regardless of 80% of allocation made to the issuer designed asset allocation portfolio.
data.change: There is a one-time opportunity to change the Income Option on the activation date for an additional annual fee of 0.25%.
data.effectChangeOwnership: Change in ownership will result in termination of rider except, change is due to marriage, divorce, or death prior to the activation date. However, at least one of the original named Covered Person(s) must remain in the contract.
data.gmwbCancellation: May be cancelled on or after the 5th benefit anniversary.
data.gmwbTermination: Benefit will automatically terminate upon earliest of - 1) annuitization, 2) surrender, 3) death, or 4) benefit base reduces to zero.
data.spousalContinuationOption: A surviving spouse may elect to continue benefit after the death of owner.
data.subsequentPremium: Subsequent Purchase Payments are not allowed after owner's and/or annuitant's attained age 80 with optional living benefit. Subsequent Eligible Purchase Payments increase the benefit base dollar for dollar and the MAW amount by the MAW % multiplied by the amount of the subsequent purchase payment.
data.partialWithdrawals: When withdrawals in a rider year exceed the maximum annual withdrawal amount, the Income Base and Income Credit Base are reduced in the same proportion that the contract value is reduced for the excess withdrawal. The maximum annual withdrawal amount is reset to the maximum annual withdrawal % multiplied by the new Benefit Base.
data.reqdMinDistributions: RMD withdrawals in excess of the MAW amount are not considered to be excess withdrawals.
data.benefitDescription: Rider provides lifetime guaranteed lifetime income plus the opportunity to increase income by locking in the greater of either the contracts Higher Anniversary Value, or an Income Base with an annual Income Credit. Owner have 3 different Income Options to choose from and rider offers flexibility to make one-time change to owner's initial elections of 1) covered person and 2) income option on the Activation Date.
data.benefitBaseGeneral: Income Base is determined by the Higher Anniversary Value on annual basis. Initially the Income Base is equal to the initial purchase payment, thereafter is increased by each subsequent Purchase Payment received, and is reduced proportionally by any withdrawals taken prior to the Activation Date and Excess Withdrawals taken on or after the Activation Date. Income base on each Benefit Year Anniversary, automatically locked in to the greater of - 1) highest Anniversary Value, or 2) current Income Base increased by any available Income Credit. Additionally, issuer provides Income Credit of 7.0% on every benefit year anniversary , prior to the activation date. Income Base is used to determine the Maximum Withdrawal Amount that can be withdrawn under the rider. Maximum amount withdrawn on or after the activation date, while contract value is greater than zero, is equal to the Maximum Annual Withdrawal Percentage multiplied by the Income Base. Protected Income Payment, if contract value reduces to zero, but Income Base is greater than zero after the Activation Date, is equal to the Protected Income Payment Percentage multiplied by the Income Base.
data.benefitBaseNoWithdrawal: Prior to the Activation Date, the Income Base is automatically increased to the greater of (1) the Higher Anniversary Value; or (2) the current Income Base plus the Income Credit. If the Income Base is increased to a Higher Anniversary Value, the Income Credit Base is also automatically increased to that Higher Anniversary Value. The Income Credit Base is not increased if an Income Credit is added to the Income Base.
data.benefitBaseWithdrawal: Income Base is used to determine the Maximum Withdrawal Amount that can be withdrawn under the rider. Maximum amount withdrawn on or after the activation date, while contract value is greater than zero, is equal to the Maximum Annual Withdrawal Percentage multiplied by the Income Base. Maximum amount withdrawn if contract value reduces to zero, but Income Base is greater than zero after the Activation Date, is equal to the Protected Income Payment Percentage multiplied by the Income Base.
data.notes: Owner can change the Income Option on the Activation Date (quarterly fee rate can increase no more than 0.1625%) the Lifetime Income Option Change Fee will be assessed and deducted from your contract value starting on the first Benefit Quarter Anniversary following the Activation Date and quarterly thereafter.
data.withdrawalNotes: Protected Income Payment Percentage will be 4.50% for single life & 4.25% for joint life for option I, if the Income Base is increased to a new Highest Anniversary Value on or after the covered person's (65th birthday).
data.chargeNotes: Rider fees are deducted on quarterly anniversaries of the rider effective date and begin on the date the rider takes effect.
data.feeOption: The fee rate can increase or decrease no more than 0.10% each quarter (0.40%/4). The change in fee percentage is determined by the change in Volatility Index (VIX) decreases or increases, the fee rate will decrease or increase accordingly.
data.restrictionOnSubAcctNotes: Owner must allocate 20% in Secure Value Account and remaining 80% must be in the specified sub-accounts and DCA fixed account under group A & B, where 50% of this 80% allocation must be made under the variable investment options specified under group B.
